04618nam a22006015i 9780691258904DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232001nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912589047 a10.1515/97806912589042doi  a(DE-B1597)677677  a(OCoLC)1414454933  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDS885.5.O9bA3 2001eb 7aHIS0210002bisacsh04a328.52/0922221 aYukio, Ozaki, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Autobiography of Ozaki Yukio :bThe Struggle for Constitutional Government in Japan /cOzaki Yukio. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2023] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (416 p.) :b7 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustration -- tTranslator’s Note -- tAbout the Translators -- tForeword -- t1. The Birth of Constitutional Government in Japan -- t2. In Preparation for a National Parliament -- t3. Around the Time of the Security Ordinance -- t4. The Early Days of the Parliament -- t5. From the Matsukata-Ōkuma Government to the Ōkuma-Itagaki Government -- t6. The Birth of the Seiyu¯kai -- t7. The Era of the Russo-Japanese War -- t8. The Movement to Protect Constitutional Government -- t9. The Ōkuma Cabinet Era -- t10. The State of Domestic and Foreign Policy after the War -- t11. The Suffrage Movement and Arms Control -- t12. From Taishō to Shōwa -- t13. Japan in the Storm -- t14. The Pacific War and Its Aftermath -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOzaki Yukio, who was returned to his seat in the Japanese Diet twenty-five times, served in that body from its inception in 1890 to 1953. He was several times a cabinet member and, for ten years, mayor of Tokyo. A strong advocate of representative government, he both witnessed and propelled Japan's transformation from a late feudal society to a modern state. His autobiography, available in English for the first time, gives an insider's account of key episodes and leaders over seven decades of Japanese history.Ozaki's political life spanned the Meiji rise to power and Japan's defeat in World War II, and he played a significant role in each phase of that epic. As a young reporter, he gained preeminence with incisive calls for supremacy in East Asia. A European trip that showed him the devastation of World War I converted him to advocacy of arms reduction and international cooperation. He watched with dismay as Japan encountered isolation and military disaster. Known for the courage of his convictions, he became a marked man, carrying a death poem in his pocket. His sturdy independence survived the American Occupation, as he deplored his associates' readiness to heed occupation dictates.Ozaki's story reverberates with the immediacy of his personal knowledge of every major Japanese political figure for three-quarters of a century. It is the account of a man who made history as well as writing it. His story is the story of modern Japan. Through it, readers will gain first-hand knowledge of Japanese constitutional history, one with rich relevance for contemporary Japanese politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aStatesmenzJapanvBiography. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh1 aHara, Fujiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJansen, Marius B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691258904?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691258904423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691258904/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSH